"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by STOPAIDS Introduction\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSTOPAIDS is the network of 80 UK agencies working since 1986 to secure an effective global response to HIV and AIDS.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWe endorse the submission from the Bond Disability\n and Development Working Group and make a few simple points bringing the perspective of a network focused on HIV and AIDS.\n&#xa0;\nContext\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDisabled people’s access to information and programmes addressing HIV and AIDS is often inadequate. This flows from a numbe\nr of barriers and including: \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nprevailing cultural norms which assume that disabled people do not have sexual identities and/or are not vulnerable to sexual violence which puts them at risk of HIV infection;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nthe inability of mainstream development agencies\n to reach out to and communicate effectively with disabled people;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nthe reluctance of influential agencies such as DFID to fully prioritise the rights of disabled people.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAdditionally, and for the first time since the start of the HIV epidemic 32 years ago, \n10% of the adult population living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries is aged 50 or older\n. This brings a\nn increased need to ensure equitable and sustainable a\nccess to affordable, innovative medicines in order to off-set the increased risks of \nmore chronic illnesses and disability\n.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nRecommendations\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn its recent publication, \nTowards Zero Infections – Two Years On\n, \nDFID identifies disabled people as being \na\n \n’hard to reach’ group. We therefore \nrecommend that DFID articulate clear goals for how it will use its financial and political influence to advance the position of disabled people in the context of the HIV epidemic in order to (a) increase disabled peopl\ne’s access to prevention, treatment, care and support and (b) reduce people’s vulnerability to disability resulting from a lack of e\nquitable and sustainable access to affordable, innovative medicines\n.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDrawing on the programmatic experience of our members \nwe specifically recommend:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nbuilding the capacity of disabled people’s organisations to provide information on HIV/AIDS;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nencouraging the disaggregation of data in all reporting on prevention, treatment and care and support programmes;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nrecognising\n the vulnerability of disabled people, and disabled women and girls in particular, to sexual violence which increases their vulnerability to HIV and AIDS;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nensur\ning\n that health facilities are physically and linguistically accessible for disabled people, extending Lynne Featherstone\n’\ns recent commitment that all new school funded by DFID would be accessible to CWD and extending this to health centres;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nrecognis\ning the a\ndditional stigma and poverty facing disabled people who are also HIV positive.\n&#xa0;\nDecember 2013\n&#xa0;\n See UNAIDS \nHIV and Aging \nreport, November 2013 \nhttp://www.unaids.org/en/media/unaids/contentassets/documents/unaidspublication/2013/20131101_JC2563_hiv-and-aging_en.pdf\n \nhttp://stopaids.org.uk/our-actions/access-to-medicines/\n \nhttp://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/Towards%20zero%20infections%20two%20years%20on_0.pdf\n"